# Evidence Hierarchy

| Evidence Type | Strength |
|---------------|----------|
| Systematic Review / Meta-analysis | ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐ |
| Randomized Controlled Trial | ⭐⭐⭐⭐☆ |
| Observational Study | ⭐⭐⭐☆☆ |
| Survey / Case Study | ⭐⭐☆☆☆ |
| Expert Opinion | ⭐⭐☆☆☆ |
| Anecdotal Experience | ⭐☆☆☆☆ |

---

# Final Assessment

Claim B is supported by the strongest evidence because it synthesizes findings from numerous peer-reviewed studies while acknowledging uncertainty and limitations. This makes its conclusions more reliable than those based on small surveys or personal experiences.

Claim A provides useful preliminary insights but lacks methodological rigor. Claim C relies entirely on anecdotal evidence and should not be used to support broad conclusions.

---

# Reflection

## What I Learned

Not all evidence carries the same weight. The quality of a conclusion depends not only on whether evidence exists, but also on how that evidence was collected, analyzed, and validated.

---

## What I'd Do Differently

Review the methodology of the studies included in the systematic review to assess their individual quality and determine whether the overall conclusions are well supported.

